#tag("co-vector-of-Hermitian-tensor") 
#indent[
  $ϕ$ derives the co-vector of #link(<Hermitian-tensor>)[]
  $
    dmat( delim: #none ,
      ⨀^(* 2) ℂ^2 , ⟶ , ℝ ;
      #p , ⟿ , ϕ^† #p^⬨ ϕ
    )
  $
  where $#p^⬨$ is #link(<parity>)[]. Since $#p ∈ ⨀^(* 2) ℂ^2$ is a Hermitian matrix, then $(#p^⬨)^† = #p^⬨$, so $(ϕ^† #p^⬨ ϕ)^† = ϕ^† #p^⬨ ϕ$, so $ϕ^† #p^⬨ ϕ in ℝ$
  
  It can be considered that $#p$ acts symmetrically on the two slots $ϕ^† (#p^⬨ ϕ) = (ϕ^† (#p^⬨ ϕ))^† = (#p^⬨ ϕ)^† ϕ$

  The base of the co-vector space $σ^0,σ^1,σ^2,σ^3 ∈ Lin(ℝ^(1,3) -> ℝ)$ gives the coefficients of the co-vector $ϕ^† (σ^μ)^⬨ ϕ in ℝ$

  $(1/2,0)$ action is derived to the action on the co-vector $ϕ$
  $
    (A ϕ)^† #p^⬨ (A ϕ) 
    &= ϕ^† (A^† #p^⬨ A) ϕ \
    &= ϕ^† (A^(-1) #p^⬨ (A^†)^(-1))^⬨ ϕ & "use" #link(<property-of-paristy>)[] \
    &= ϕ^† ((A^(⊙ * 2))^(-1) #p)^⬨ ϕ 
  $

  The parity dual of $ϕ^† #p^⬨ ϕ$, $ϕ$ derives the co-vector

  $ #p ⟿ ϕ^† #p ϕ $

  $(0,1/2)$ action $A^†$ is derived to the action on the co-vector

  Similarly, co-vectors can also be defined for anti-Hermitian
  $
    dmat( delim: #none ,
      ⋀^(* 2) ℂ^2 , ⟶ , Im(ℂ) ;
      P , ⟿ , ϕ^† P^⬨ ϕ
    )
  $
  For conjugate 2 order tensors
  $
    dmat( delim: #none ,
      ⨂^(* 2) ℂ^2 , ⟶ , ℂ ;
      P , ⟿ , ϕ^† P^⬨ ϕ
    )
  $
]
