#tag("Dirac-eq-plane-wave") Plane wave solution $vec(Φ, Ψ) e^(- #i p x)$ with $p^2 = m^2$ and $(mat( #p ;,#p^⬨) - m mat(,𝟙;𝟙)) vec(Φ,Ψ) = 0$ 
  
The latter is a linear equation, so the solution is not difficult. The solution space is two-dimensional, and the solution can be written as $vec(Φ,Ψ) = vec(#p^(⬨ 1/2) ξ, #p^(1/2) ξ), ξ ∈ ℂ^2$

#tag("squrae-root-of-spacetime-momentum-spinor-representation") 
#indent[
  Although it might be possible to use the eigenvalues of the Hermite matrix $#p$ ($p_0 ± (p_0^2 - m^2)^(1/2)$), we will calculate it directly here. let $#p = #q^2$ or
  $
    mat(
      p_0 + p_1 , p_2 + #i p_3 ;
      p_2 - #i p_3 , p_0 - p_1
    )
    = mat(
      (q_0 + q_1)^2 + q_2^2 + q_3^2 , 2 q_0 (q_2 + #i q_3) ;
      2 q_0 (q_2 - #i q_3) , (q_0 - q_1)^2 + q_2^2 + q_3^2
    )
  $
  ==>
  $
    p_0 &= q_0^2 + q_1^2 + q_2^2 + q_3^2 \
    p_1 &= 2 q_0 q_1 \
    p_2 + #i p_3 &=  2 q_0 (q_2 + #i q_3) 
  $
  ==> Use $p_1^2 + p_2^2 + p_3^2 = p_0^2 - m^2$
  $
    p_0 = q_0^2 + 1/(4 q_0^2) (p_0^2 - m^2)
  $
  Quadratic equation for $q_0^2$: $(q_0^2)^2 - p_0 (q_0^2) + 1/4 (p_0^2 - m^2)$, solution
  $
    q_0^2 = 1/2 (p_0 ± m)
  $
  ==>
  $
    q_0 &= (1/2 (p_0 ± m))^(1/2) \
    &= frac(p_0 + m,(2 (p_0 ± m))^(1/2)) \

    i = 1,2,3 => q_i &= frac(p_i,(2 (p_0 ± m))^(1/2))
  $
  or 
  $
    #p^(1/2) &= frac(
      #p ± m 𝟙 ,
      (2 (p_0 ± m))^(1/2)
    ) \
    "and " 
    #p^(⬨ 1/2) &= frac(
      #p^⬨ ± m 𝟙 ,
      (2 (p_0 ± m))^(1/2)
    )
  $
  Still Hermite. Calculation yields
  $
    #p^(1/2) #p^(⬨ 1/2) = m = #p^(⬨ 1/2) #p^(1/2)
  $

  *Example* 
  #indent[
    If $p = (p_0,p_1,0,0), p_0 > 0$, then $#p^(1/2) = mat((p_0 + p_1)^(1/2);,(p_0 - p_1)^(1/2))$ and $#p^(⬨ 1/2) = mat((p_0 - p_1)^(1/2);,(p_0 + p_1)^(1/2))$. If $p_1 = 0$ as well, then $vec(#p^(1/2) ξ, #p^(⬨ 1/2) ξ) = p_0^(1/2) vec(ξ,ξ)$
  ]

  $vec(#p^(1/2) ξ, #p^(⬨ 1/2) ξ)^† vec(#p^(1/2) ξ, #p^(⬨ 1/2) ξ) &= ξ^† (#p + #p^⬨) ξ \
  &= (2 p_0) |ξ|^2 \
  &= (tr #p) |ξ|^2$ 
]

1,3 metric square root or $∆$ square root $mat(#p^⬨;,#p) mat(#p ;,#p^⬨) = (det #p) mat(𝟙;,𝟙)$. But you can also use $#p ⇝ mat(,#p^⬨;#p)$ to get the true square $mat(,#p^⬨;#p)^2 = (det #p) 𝟙$. Since $mat(#p ;,#p^⬨)^2 != (det #p) 𝟙$, the transformation between $mat(#p ;,#p^⬨)$ and $mat(,#p ; #p^⬨)$ is not a coordinate change $T^(-1) ⋅ M ⋅ T$ in $GL(4,ℂ)$.

#tag("motivation-of-gauge-field?") 
#indent[
  Some issues were ignored

  The tangent projective light cone bundle is well-defined

  Do we really need $ℂ^2$ fields or $ℂℙ^1$ fields? There are too many choices for lifting $ℂℙ^1$ fields to $ℂ^2$ fields (or lifting to $ℂ^2 ∖ 0$ fields), unlike $SO(1,3)$ lifting to $SL(2,ℂ)$ where there are only two. On curved manifolds, there might not even be a continuous single-valued lift.

  The $ℂ^2$ bundle over curved spacetime can be directly defined in the bundle coordinates of the $SO(1,3)$ principal bundle (orthonormal frame bundle). When changing coordinates, $SL(2,ℂ)$ is automatically derived from $SO(1,3)$.

  In curved spacetime, the covariant derivative of spinor fields needs to be handled and derived from #link(<metric-connection>)[]. 
  
  For derivatives, an orthonormal frame should be used instead of a coordinate frame, i.e., using the $SO(1,3), SL(2,ℂ)$ principal bundle.

  Although we already have a $ℂ^2$ bundle, lifting $ℂℙ^1$ to $ℂ^2$ introduces additional symmetry. We can multiply the spinor $ϕ(x)$ by $a(x) = |a(x)| exp(θ #i) ∈ GL(1,ℂ) = ℝ_(> 0) × #U (1)$ to change the gauge to $a(x) ϕ(x)$, which remains the same in the projective $ℂℙ^1$.

  Changing the gauge is incompatible with taking derivatives in the tangent space in bundle coordinates, so an additional structure --- #link(<principal-bundle-connection>)[connection] --- must be introduced.
  
  There are many possible connections.
  
  There are connections that cannot be made locally flat; in every gauge, the connection field cannot be eliminated.
  
  Similar to gravity, the concept of local flat connection <==> local curvature 0 is needed, and the connection is chosen by minimizing curvature.
  
  Even if the topology of the spacetime base manifold is non-trivial, different bundle types may exist.

  If simple conserved currents for the action are desired, use $#U (1)$ gauge transformations instead of $ℂ ∖ 0 = #U (1) × ℝ_(> 0)$. $#U (1)$ does not change the Lagrangian action, which simplifies calculations when computing conserved currents (cf. the case of scalar fields).

  One problem is that the gauge bundle does not seem to be directly related to the tangent bundle.
  
  It seems necessary to consider all types of $#U (1)$ bundle types based on the underlying manifold simultaneously

  In the homotopy sense, $ℝ^(p,q)$ has only one type of $#U (1)$ bundle type
]
#tag("spin-connection")
#indent[
  The $SO(1,3)$ #link(<principal-bundle>)[frame bundle] derived from the tangent bundle metric and the #link(<principal-bundle-connection>)[connection] derived from #link(<metric-connection>)[] are expressed as $Γ$ is locally type $(ℝ^(1,3))^⊺ ⊗ so(1,3)$, acting on the tangent field $ℝ^(1,3)$ by $∂ + Γ$

  The way to derive the spin-connection is to #link(<square-root-of-Lorentz-Lie-algebra>)[map the $so(1,3)$ part of the induced metric-connection $Γ$ to $sl(2,ℂ)$] in the orthonormal-frame, obtaining the connection of the $SL(2,ℂ)$ bundle, locally type $(ℝ^(1,3))^⊺ ⊗ ℂ^2$, acting on the spinor field $ℂ^2$ by $∂ + ω$ with $ω = ω^(μ ν) 1/4 [σ_(μ),σ_(ν)]_(⬨)$
]
